1. Introduction to TDD
Test Driven Development (TDD) is a software development approach where tests are written before code.
It follows the "Test First" principle.
TDD improves code quality and reliability.
It helps detect bugs early in development.
It follows the Red-Green-Refactor cycle.

2. TDD Cycle
Red: Write a test that fails.
Green: Write minimum code to pass the test.
Refactor: Improve the code without changing functionality.
Repeat this cycle for every new feature.
This ensures clean and maintainable code.

3. Introduction to Unit Testing
Unit testing verifies individual methods or classes.
It checks whether each unit works correctly.
It helps find bugs at an early stage.
Unit tests are fast and easy to automate.
JUnit is the most popular unit testing framework in Java.

4. JUnit Framework
JUnit is an open-source Java testing framework.
It provides annotations like @Test and @BeforeEach.
Assertions verify expected outputs.
Tests can be executed automatically.
It simplifies Java application testing.

5. Test Structure
AAA stands for Arrange, Act, and Assert.
Arrange prepares test data.
Act executes the method under test.
Assert verifies the expected result.
This structure makes tests easy to understand.

6. Advanced JUnit Features
Parameterized tests run the same test with different inputs.
Test suites combine multiple test classes.
Exception testing checks expected exceptions.
Timeout testing limits execution time.
Execution order controls the sequence of tests.

7. Mockito Basics
Mockito is a Java mocking framework.
It creates mock objects for testing.
Stubbing defines mock behavior.
Verify checks method interactions.
It isolates code from external dependencies.

8. Testing Spring Applications with JUnit & Mockito
Spring Boot supports unit and integration testing.
Controllers, services, and repositories can be tested separately.
@SpringBootTest loads the Spring context.
@MockBean replaces real dependencies with mocks.
It improves application reliability.

9. Mocking External Dependencies
Mock databases instead of using real ones.
Mock REST APIs to avoid network calls.
Mock file operations during testing.
Mocking makes tests faster and independent.
It ensures consistent test results.

10. Introduction to Automation Testing
Automation testing uses tools to execute tests automatically.
It reduces manual effort and saves time.
Automated tests are faster than manual tests.
It improves testing accuracy.
It is widely used in Continuous Integration (CI).

11. Types of Automated Tests
Unit tests check individual methods.
Integration tests verify module interactions.
Functional tests validate business requirements.
End-to-End tests verify complete workflows.
Performance tests measure speed and scalability.

12. Automation Testing Process
Select the appropriate automation tool.
Define the scope of automation.
Design and develop test scripts.
Execute automated tests.
Maintain and update test scripts regularly.

13. Test Automation Frameworks
Data-Driven Framework uses external test data.
Keyword-Driven Framework uses predefined keywords.
Hybrid Framework combines multiple approaches.
Frameworks improve code reuse.
They simplify test maintenance.

14. Popular Automation Tools
Selenium automates web applications.
Appium is used for mobile testing.
JUnit and TestNG are Java testing frameworks.
Cucumber supports Behavior Driven Development (BDD).
Cypress is popular for modern web application testing.

15. SLF4J
SLF4J is a logging facade for Java.
It supports different logging frameworks.
Parameterized logging improves performance.
It provides log levels like INFO, WARN, and ERROR.
It simplifies application logging.

16. Lombok – Introduction & Core Annotations
Lombok reduces Java boilerplate code.
@Getter and @Setter generate accessor methods.
@Data combines common annotations.
@Builder simplifies object creation.
It improves code readability and productivity.

17. Lombok – Advanced Usage & IDE Integration
@Slf4j automatically creates a logger.
@Value creates immutable classes.
Advanced @Builder supports flexible object creation.
Annotation processing must be enabled in the IDE.
Lombok works with IntelliJ IDEA and Eclipse through plugins.